Additional Server:
A new server is added so infrastructure components can be separated.
Instead of running the web server, application server, and database on the same machine, each component can run on its own server.

Additional Load Balancer:
A second HAProxy load balancer is added and configured as a cluster with the first one.
This removes the load balancer as a single point of failure.
If one load balancer fails, the other can continue sending traffic to the infrastructure.

Load Balancer Cluster:
The load balancers can be configured in an Active-Passive setup.
The active load balancer receives traffic.
The passive load balancer waits as a backup and takes over if the active one fails.

Split Components:
The web server, application server, and database are split onto separate servers.

Web Server:
The Nginx web server handles HTTP/HTTPS requests from users.
It serves static files and forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

Application Server:
The application server runs the backend logic of the website.
It processes requests, executes the application code, and communicates with the database.

Database Server:
The MySQL database server stores persistent data.
It handles data reads and writes requested by the application server.

Why this infrastructure is better:
Splitting components makes the infrastructure easier to scale.
Each layer can be improved independently.
For example, more web servers can be added if there is more traffic.
More application servers can be added if the application logic needs more processing power.
The database server can be optimized separately for storage and queries.

Issues improved:
The load balancer is no longer a single point of failure because there are two HAProxy instances in a cluster.
The services are easier to maintain because each major component has its own server.
The infrastructure is more scalable than having everything on the same machines.
